  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions worldwide. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by disguising its true origin. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions designed to obscure the source and ownership of the funds.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, tax evasion, and terrorism financing. Laws against money laundering are designed to disrupt the financial infrastructure that supports these illicit activities and to promote transparency and integrity in the financial system.\n\nIn many countries, including the United States, the European Union, and China, anti-money laundering (AML) laws require financial institutions and other regulated entities to implement measures to detect and report suspicious transactions. Penalties for engaging in or facilitating money laundering can include significant fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences. \n\nIn China, for example, the criminal justice system strictly enforces laws against money laundering under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law** and the **Criminal Law**. Chinese authorities actively collaborate with international organizations to combat money laundering and related financial crimes.",
